l-1-pattern-calculation-before-cutting/">Dress with Separately Cut Cups <span>(15)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="19"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-introductory-tutorial/">Bodysuit with Corset Cups <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="24"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-measurement/">Party Dress <span>(17)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#544">Transparent corsets  <span>(4)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="25"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-cutting-a-mock-up/">Corset with Drapery <span>(20)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="26"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-and-the-throw-over-sewing-technique/">Corset with Integral Straps <span>(27)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="34"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model/">Corset with 3-Part Cups <span>(22)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="76"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-5/">Corset with a Fancy Cut-Out <span>(22)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#3082">Decoration Techniques  <span>(9)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="83"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials/">Rhinestones Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="84"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-glue-on-half-pearls/">Additional Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="85"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-thick-decoration-element/">Thick Decoration Elements <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="86"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong>Dressmaker’s Treasury will equip you with a range of necessary tools and techniques which every professional must possess for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>It will help you get more confident. You will know how to: </strong></p><ul><li>Choose the right strategy for making a garment after your first meeting with the client;</li><li>Take necessary measurements correctly and prepare and fill out an order form;</li><li>Choose the right basic pattern and adjust it after your client’s measurements with the help of automatic pattern adjustments calculation tables;</li><li>Avoid common mistakes which result in ill-fitting necklines by choosing the right sewing technique.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;5h 16m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-32-side-dart-opening/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-32-side-dart-opening/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2017-12-02T13:36:41+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2017-12-02T13:36:41+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2017"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 32. Side Dart Opening."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 32. Side Dart Opening."><meta itemprop="description" content="Side Dart Opening. There is basically no easing-in for size zero with 68cm Under-Bust Circumference and 72cm Bust Circumference"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding and Evening Dresses. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding and evening dresses. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 32. Side Dart Opening.</h1><p>Now that we have gone through some theory, you know that there is a side dart on the cup which emerges when you use a sew-in cup pattern for seamless integration into a corset pattern.</p><p>When you sew a corset with seamlessly integrated cups correctly, this side dart gets taken in with the fabric eased in under the half-circle bone along the bottom border of the cup on the side corset piece.</p><p><strong>I have prepared a special Table of Suggested Dart Widths and Amounts of Easing-In to help you define how much fabric you need to ease in depending on dart width. You can find the table in the Appendix. </strong></p><p><strong>It often results in a poor fit when the side cup piece is not eased in correctly along the half-circle bone. </strong>You will eventually develop a natural feel for how much to ease in and will no longer need a table for it. But you do need some guidelines when you are still a beginner.</p><p><strong>You can check yourself by comparing your estimated amount of easing-in with values from my table. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2032.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Before explaining how to use the table, let me tell you that corset cups cut one piece with corset body are nothing too hard! </strong>I encourage you to practice as much as you can, and you will get skilled very soon.</p><p><strong>You must also know</strong> that the table represents average values. They are mainly intended to be used for reference to avoid gross mistakes.</p><p><strong>And now let us study some theory.</strong></p><p><strong>In Russia, bras are classified into several size groups based on Under-Bust Circumference or Band Size.</strong> They are “Small” (UBC 68cm-72cm), “Medium” (UBC 80cm), and “Large” (UBC 96cm).</p><p><strong>Every group is associated with several Cup Sizes based on the difference between Bust Circumference and Under-Bust Circumference.</strong> A difference of 12cm points at size zero (0), a difference of 14cm – at size one (1), 16cm – at size two (2), and 18cm – at size three (3), etc.</p><p><strong>Recommended amount of easing-in is given in centimeters in the column titled “Ease In.” This is about how much you need to ease in on the side cup piece when putting a half-circle bone along its bottom border. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2032.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Let us look at the small sizes.</strong></p><p><strong>There is basically no easing-in for size zero with 68cm Under-Bust Circumference and 72cm Bust Circumference. </strong>In other words, it is not worth easing in such small cups because it will be enough to press them on a special cup pressing mould after putting bones on them. No additional volume will be required!</p><p>A woman with small breasts will feel more comfortable in a corset with bones in the cups than in a corset sewn in the simplified technique, i.e. without bones in the cups. <strong>The bones will form a beautiful corset silhouette and make the bust appear fuller. </strong></p><p>And believe me that these cups will never look too large as long as you adjust the pattern correctly! It is wrong to say that cups with bones in them become too large and you cannot achieve a tight enough fit. This is nothing but the dressmaker’s mistake!</p><p><strong>If your cups turn out to be too large, you can make the following conclusion: </strong></p><p>- The measurements were taken incorrectly,</p><p>- The pattern was adjusted to client’s size incorrectly,</p><p>- You did not stick with the suggested sewing technique.</p><p>These three components are responsible for the fit of the corset!</p><p><strong>Do not ease in small cups and they will have the right size and volume! </strong></p><p><strong>What happens with a slightly larger cup size? </strong></p><p><strong>We are still looking at the small sizes. </strong></p><p><strong>Size one (1)</strong> requires that you ease in 1cm.</p><p><strong>Size two (2) requires that you ease in 2cm.</strong></p><p><strong>Of course, it is rather hard to ease in as much as 2cm on a relatively small piece. </strong>In most cases, you can only ease in 1.5cm. When you press a cup with bones on the cup pressing mould to improve its shape, the eased-in fabric will spread evenly. But when you put it on a flat ironing table to press the corset under the cups, closer to the side, you will notice a small wave left after the easing-in. Unfortunately, it is not always possible to iron it away, and sometimes you must make a small under-bust dart there.</p><p><strong>I often demonstrate it in my courses that a small under-bust dart tends to get formed automatically on the lining of a small-size corset. </strong>But there is no need in transferring it on the face fabric! It is usually very small and hardly noticeable and you can re-distribute it vertically along the side corset piece when putting the face fabric in place.</p><p><strong>I will be happy if you learn to ease in corset cups not just mechanically but with a clear understanding of why you need to make it 2cm for this particular cup size. </strong></p><p><strong>And so let me highlight it again: </strong>it is the width of the opening of that unclosed side dart which was formed on the side corset piece when we were making the basic pattern. It is this very dart we want to close by easing in the cup. And it is why there is an under-bust dart on the lining.</p><p><strong>Let us see what happens with larger cups.</strong></p><p><strong>We are looking at the medium band size, cup size one (1). </strong></p><p><strong>We need to close a dart with a width of 2.2cm. </strong>It is basically impossible to ease in 2.2cm despite the fact that the piece is a little larger than in the previous case. Judging from my experience, you cannot ease in more than 1.2-1.5cm. And this is why that under-bust dart arises again. You will see it in the table in the following tutorials when we talk about adjusting standard patterns.</p><p><strong>I believe it is best to explain the reasons why this under-bust dart arises right now. </strong>It arises because we cannot give the cup its proper round shape without it. And that means this under-bust dart will be made not only on the lining, but also on the face of the garment.</p><p><strong>The depth of this under-bust dart will be about 1cm if you manage to ease in 1.2cm-1.5cm.</strong></p><p><strong>Let us look at larger cups. </strong></p><p><strong>We are still in the same medium size group. Let us take cup size two (2). </strong></p><p><strong>This time, we need to close a dart with a width of 3.2cm. </strong>It is obvious that the depth of the under-bust dart will be about 1.7cm if you ease in 1.5cm on the cup.</p><p>Please remember that these table values are approximate and you should only use them for reference. A lot depends on your client’s figure and measurements. We will talk about it in more detail in the tutorials dedicated to pattern adjustments.</p><p><strong>I made this table to show you where the under-bust dart comes from and how wide it should be, at least roughly. </strong></p><p><strong>A careful look through the table is enough to understand that larger bust or cup sizes imply wider under-bust dart openings. </strong></p><p><strong>Of course, the cups themselves become larger when we move to the large size group, which means we can ease in up to 2cm. </strong></p><p><strong>Let us take, for example, cup size two (2). </strong></p><p><strong>We need to close a dart with a width of 5.6cm. </strong></p><p>Part of this dart (and namely, 2cm) can be closed by easing in the cup. The remaining part will be closed by an under-bust dart with a depth of 3.6cm. But the total value must be 5.6cm, or else the cups will not have enough volume! <strong>This is very important!</strong></p><p><strong>Therefore, the under-bust dart is made both on the face and on the lining. And you ease in the cups on the lining in addition. </strong>And when you join the face with the lining, you try to either flatten this 2cm easing-in or re-distribute it vertically along the joined pieces.</p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20boat.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Boat-Neck Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20strapless.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Strapless Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20V%20neck.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> V-Neck Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/corset%20-%20neck%20strap.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Corset with Halter-Neck Strap</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/corset%20-%20shoulder%20strap.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Corset with Shoulder Strap</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patter